The conversion price is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Conversion Price}&=\frac{\text{Face Value of Bond}}{\text{Conversion Ratio in Shares}}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$1,000}{18\space\text{shares}}\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$55.56}
\end{aligned}$$

The face value of the bond is divided by the conversion ratio in shares to determine the conversion price. 

Therefore, the conversion price is $55.56.

Now, the conversion premium is solved below: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Conversion Premium}&=\frac{\left(\text{Conversion Price-Current Stock Price}\right)}{\text{Current Stock Price}}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\left(\$55.56-\$45\right)}{\$45}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$10.56}{\$45}\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{0.2347\space\text{or}\space23.47\%}
\end{aligned}$$

The difference between conversion price and current stock price is divided by the current stock price to determine the conversion premium. 

Therefore, the conversion premium is 23.47%.

The stock price in this requirement is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Stock Price}&=\frac{\text{Straight Bond Value}}{\text{Conversion Ratio}}\\[20pt]
&=\frac{\$741.20}{18}\\[20pt]
&=\boxed{\$41.18}
\end{aligned}$$

The straight bond value is divided by the conversion ratio in shares to determine the stock price. 

Therefore, the stock price should be $41.18 for the straight bond value and conversion value to be equal.

Using the equation in Step 15, the total value of the option is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Value of Option}&=(\$960-\$810)+(\$810-\$741.20)\\[15pt]
&=\$150+\$68.80\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$218.80}
\end{aligned}$$

Thus, the total value of the option is $218.80.
